How Pumpkin Growing Power Differs Across the U.S.
Every fall, growers across North America compete to grow the heaviest pumpkins. But not all pumpkins, or all regions, are created equal. Our analysis finds that pumpkin weight varies significantly based on genetics, location, and even yearly conditions.
We analyzed competition data from the Great Pumpkin Commonwealth (GPC) from 2013 to 2020. While the competition is global, our focus here is on the United States, where the majority of entries are recorded. Using over 6,000 entries, we explored how seed genetics and regional growing conditions impact pumpkin weight.
Genetic Factors: Seed Mothers and Pollinator Fathers
Genetics plays a major role in how heavy a pumpkin can grow. We first looked at the “seed mother” lineage—the maternal side of the pumpkin family.

The data shows that pumpkins from seed mothers like “2008 Neptune” and “2145 McMullen” consistently produce heavier entries, while others like “81 Wolf” have lower median weights. This highlights that superior seed lines can offer growers a significant advantage.
The pollinator father’s side tells a similar story.








Notably, pumpkins pollinated by “2009 Wallace” lines stood out with much heavier median weights, compared to more generic “self” or “open” pollination sources. The importance of strategic breeding is clear: winning pumpkins often come from carefully selected parentage.
Regional Trends: How Pumpkin Weight Changes Over Time
Location matters too. Environmental factors such as soil quality, temperature, and growing culture differ across regions. We zoomed into the six U.S. states and provinces with the most competition entries: California, Michigan, Ohio, Ontario, Wisconsin, and a general “Other” category.

From 2013 to 2020, no state showed dramatic year-over-year growth, but there were fluctuations. California showed relatively higher weight spikes around 2017, while Ontario and Wisconsin had steadier, flatter trends. Michigan and Ohio displayed more variability, hinting at changing growing conditions or participant turnover.
Geographic Distribution: Where the Heaviest Pumpkins Are Grown
To visualize the regional differences more clearly, we mapped the average pumpkin weight across U.S. states.

The Midwest, especially states like Ohio and Michigan, consistently produced heavier pumpkins compared to southern or coastal states. This suggests that cooler climates, specific soil types, or stronger pumpkin-growing traditions could favor giant pumpkin cultivation.
Conclusion: Winning Takes Both Genes and Geography
Our analysis shows that growing a giant pumpkin isn’t just a matter of luck. Genetics—both seed mothers and pollinator fathers—have a major influence on potential size. Meanwhile, geography—the local environment and growing conditions—also plays a critical role.
In short, the best pumpkin growers combine the right seeds with the right place. As competition intensifies, understanding and optimizing both factors will be key for those hoping to set future records.

title: 3  Alena-Han
text:
There are eight key characteristics of a strong team :
Dependence – Team members recognize their interdependence and align personal and team goals, reducing conflict and maximizing collaboration.
Trust – A foundation of trust encourages open communication, creativity, and honest feedback.
Ownership – Team members feel personally invested and committed to the team’s success.
Individual Strengths – Members are encouraged to use their unique skills and knowledge to support team objectives.
Open Communication – Clear and honest communication builds mutual understanding and reinforces trust.
Ongoing Growth – Teams support continuous learning and skill development, accepting that mistakes are part of the process.
Group Decision-Making – Decisions involve the whole team; if consensus isn’t reached, the leader steps in.
Strong Conflict Resolution – Effective teams address disagreements quickly and constructively in a safe, open environment.
Celebrate Success! Always recognize and celebrate the team’s achievements. A final meeting to express appreciation and reflect on impact helps build camaraderie and motivation for future challenges.

Alena Han, Leah Zhang
We want to look at a dataset from The Great Pumpkin Commonwealth’s (GPC) competition held in 2021, which includes numerous variables like id, weight, and ranking. Your case study will go here.
Manhattan Core Replacement Uber added 3.82 million pickups in Manhattan (south of 110th St/96th St) between 2014–2015, while taxis lost 3.83 million. Net change: -12,442 rides, showing Uber directly replaced taxis.
Outer Borough Growth In Brooklyn, Queens, and the Bronx, Uber and taxis grew. Example: Uber added 1.1M pickups in Brooklyn, while taxis gained 299k. Suggests Uber filled gaps in subway-deficient areas (e.g., Dyker Heights).
Evening Congestion Uber added 682 more pickups/hour in Manhattan’s core during 4–5 PM (2015 vs. 2014), overlapping with taxi shift changes. Data lacks dropoff locations, so traffic impact is debated.
Market Share Shifts Uber’s citywide pickup share rose from 4% (2014) to 15% (2015). Taxis retained dominance north of 59th St (25% vs. Uber’s 15%).
